== Overview == The {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} "Kokuzō Hongi" refers to them as '''Kazuraki no Kuni no Miyatsuko'''.
=== Ancestry === According to the "Kokuzō Hongi" in ''Sendai Kuji Hongi,'' Tsurugi no Nekoto, the ancestor of the {{ill|Kazuraki no Atae|ja|葛城直|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was appointed the first Kazuraki no Kuni no Miyatsuko during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' states that Tsurugi no Nekoto was a fifth-generation descendant of {{ill|Takamimusubi|ja|高皇産霊尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and a fourth-generation descendant of {{ill|Amaoshitatemi no Mikoto|ja|天押立命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
=== Clan === The Kazuraki clan (葛城氏, surname: ''Atae''). In {{ill|Emperor Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s 12th year (683), the clan was granted the surname ''Muraji'' and later ''Imiki'' in the 14th year. Although the {{ill|Kazuraki clan (Omi)|ja|臣姓葛城氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} that prospered in the 5th century descended from {{ill|Takenouchi no Sukune|ja|武内宿禰|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, both lines merged through marriage alliances.
== Territory == === Governing Area === The Miyatsuko ruled over the area known at the time as ''Kazuraki Province,'' corresponding to the Kazuraki region in {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (modern-day {{ill|Katsuge District|ja|葛上郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Katsushimo District|ja|葛下郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). This includes parts of present-day {{ill|Gose City|ja|御所市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Yamatotakada City|ja|大和高田市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Nara Prefecture.
== Clan Deity == The clan deity is unknown. However, the region contains several prominent shrines, including {{ill|Katsuragi Mikami Shrine|ja|葛城御縣神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Katsuragi Hitokotonushi Shrine|ja|葛城坐一言主神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, both classified as {{ill|Myōjin-taisha|ja|名神大社|fr|Myōjin Taisha|zh|名神大社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} under the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Notable Figures == * '''{{ill|Aratahiko|ja|荒田彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''' ** A figure from the Kofun period. His daughter, {{ill|Kazuhime|ja|葛比売|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was the mother of {{ill|Katsuragi no Sotsuhiko|ja|葛城襲津彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the imperial Kazuraki clan.
== Descendants == * {{ill|Katsuragi no Iwamura|ja|葛城磐村|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ** A Kofun-period figure. His daughter Hiroko became a consort of {{ill|Emperor Yōmei|ja|用明天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * Unnamed Daughter ** Believed to be the wife of {{ill|Soga no Iname|ja|蘇我稲目|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and mother of {{ill|Soga no Umako|ja|蘇我馬子|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * {{ill|Katsuragi Yamada Mizuko|ja|葛城山田瑞子|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ** A figure from the reign of {{ill|Emperor Kinmei|ja|欽明天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who was dispatched alongside Iname to Kibi Province as an administrator. * Katsuragi no Atae Abe ** Referenced in wooden tablets unearthed at the Heijō Palace site as ''Kosho District Katsuragi no Atae Abe'' of Etchū Province.
== References == * ''{{ill|Kokushi Daijiten|ja|国史大辞典|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' ({{ill|Yoshikawa Kōbunkan|ja|吉川弘文館|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) * {{Cite book|title=Nihon Kodai Shizoku Jinmei Jiten|author=Sakamoto Tarō and Hirano Kunio|publisher=Yoshikawa Kōbunkan}} * ''Nihon Kodaijinmei Jiten'' (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan) * ''Nihonshi Hiro Jiten'' (Yamakawa Shuppansha) * ''{{ill|Shintō Daijiten|ja|神道大辞典|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' (Rinsen Shoten) * {{ill|Tōneri Shinnō|ja|舎人親王|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''
== See Also == * {{ill|List of Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|国造#一覧|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Six Provinces of Wa|ja|倭の六県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
